<article id="node-17346">
<h1 >3.1.14.30 Work Bonus - Application</h1>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<p>This topic contains information about how the work bonus is applied to pensioners of age pension age (except <a href="../../../acronyms#pps" title="Parenting payment (single)">PPS</a>) from 1 July 2011.</p>
<h2>Application of the work bonus</h2>
<p>The work bonus is used to reduce the assessable employment income in an instalment period. An instalment period is a period of a maximum of 14 days.</p>
<p>The work bonus comprises 2 elements:</p>
<ul><li>employment income concession:
<ul><li>The first $250 of employment income earned in a 14 day instalment period is excluded from the income test.</li>
<li>Any employment income over $250 is assessed under the income test subject to the application of the employment income concession bank (see next point).</li>
</ul></li>
<li>employment income concession bank:
<ul><li>If a person's employment income for a 14 day instalment period is less than $250, the difference between the amount earned and $250 accrues in the pensioner's employment income concession bank up to a maximum of $6,500.</li>
<li>Any credit in the employment income concession bank offsets future employment income that would otherwise be assessable. Where a credit is used to reduce the amount of assessable employment income the balance remaining in the employment income concession bank reduces by the credit amount used to reduce otherwise assessable employment income. Where a person receives no pension payment in an instalment period there can be no accrual or depletion to an employment income concession bank balance. The employment income concession bank credit carries across financial years and does not expire, i.e. it remains until the eligible pensioner dies. If a pensioner goes off payment, any credit balance is retained and is reactivated if they come back on to pension.</li>
</ul></li>
</ul><h2>Treatment of partners</h2>
<p>The work bonus applies individually to each member of a couple with each member of the couple maintaining a separate employment income concession bank. After the work bonus rules are applied, the remaining assessable employment income of both partners is combined as per the usual application of the pension rate calculation process.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 8(1)-'employment income', section 1073AA Work bonus</p>
</div>
<h2>Application of work bonus for instalment period of less than 14 days</h2>
<p>A proportional rule will apply to instalment periods of less than 14 days.</p>
<p>The amount of work bonus used to calculate the reduction of employment income that is assessed under the income test is worked out using the following formula:</p>
<ul><li>Work bonus equals $250 multiplied by (number of days in the instalment period divided by 14).</li>
</ul><div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A person has employment income of $700 in an 8 day instalment period. They have no other income. As their instalment period is 8 days, the $250 concession amount is pro rata as outlined:</p>
<ul><li>Step 1 Pro rata concession: $250 Ã 8 Ã· 14 = $143</li>
<li>Step 2 Applying work bonus: $700 â $143 = $557</li>
<li>Step 3 Assessable employment income = $557</li>
</ul></div>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> Example assumes there is no balance in the employment income concession bank.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A04121" title="Social Security Act 1991">SSAct</a> section 1073AA Work bonus</p>
</div>
<h2>Instalment periods spanning across 1 July 2011</h2>
<p>Instalment periods may span over a period before and after 1 July 2011.</p>
<p>Where this occurs, the new work bonus applies for the entire instalment period that includes 1 July 2011.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Act reference:</strong> <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.au/Series/C2004A00580" title="Social Security (Administration) Act 1999">SS(Admin)Act</a> section 43 Payment by instalments</p>
</div>
